<TEXT>&#2;<DATELINE>2018-11-29</DATELINE><TITLE>Viral-Mediated mRNA Degradation for Pathogenesis</TITLE><BODY>Cellular RNA decay machinery plays a vital role in regulating gene expression by altering the stability of mRNAs in response to external stresses, including viral infection. In the primary infection, viruses often conquer the host cellâ€™s antiviral immune response by controlling the inherently cellular mRNA degradation machinery to facilitate viral gene expression and establish a successful infection. This review summarizes the current knowledge about the diverse strategies of viral-mediated regulatory RNA shutoff for pathogenesis, and particularly sheds a light on the mechanisms that viruses evolve to elude immune surveillance during infection.&#3;</BODY></TEXT>